he path forward was unclear, but there was no turning back.&lt;/p&gt;</description></item><item><title>Chapter 2: The Board</title><link>https://buzzl123.github.io/Betzalels_Writings/novels/the-long-game/chapter-2/</link><pubDate>Mon, 08 Jun 2026 22:19:09 +0300</pubDate><guid>https://buzzl123.github.io/Betzalels_Writings/novels/the-long-game/chapter-2/</guid><description>&lt;p&gt;The plan was clearer now: move through the shadows, avoid the obvious, and trust only the structure.&lt;/p&gt;</description></item><item><title>First Essay</title><link>https://buzzl123.github.io/Betzalels_Writings/essays/first-essay/</link><pubDate>Tue, 09 Jun 2026 11:40:59 +0300</pubDate><guid>https://buzzl123.github.io/Betzalels_Writings/essays/first-essay/</guid><description>&lt;p&gt;This is a placeholder essay to show how the essays section now works. You can add your own content here and it will appear as a compact card in the essays list.&lt;/p&gt;</description></item><item><title>Chapter 1: Frost Lines</title><link>https://buzzl123.github.io/Betzalels_Writings/novels/winter-city/chapter-1/</link><pubDate>Mon, 08 Jun 2026 19:29:18 +0300</pubDate><guid>https://buzzl123.github.io/Betzalels_Writings/novels/winter-city/chapter-1/</guid><description>&lt;p&gt;The city was a maze of steel and frost. Every alley carried the weight of a thousand whispers.&lt;/p&gt;</description></item></channel></rss>